    <text>
        <body>
            <div xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Zsigmond Szeremlényi to Miklós Oláh (Vienna, 1 September
                    1529)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1"> 1. Szeremlényi met János Czeglédi in Vienna, whom he
                            informed about the latest events. Their scout had gone to Pozsony and
                            returned to say that the Turks are at Kömlőd, that is, six miles from
                            Buda. 2. In the meantime, King John I had gone to Székesfehérvár, and
                            the Turkish Emperor surrounded Buda, if he has not occupied it yet. He
                            provides a status report about the siege of Esztergom. It is rumored
                            that German soldiers have driven out the Hungarians from Bratislava.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb facs="15290901_1_1.jpg"/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Praemissa servitiorum meorum commendatione, Reverendissime Domine
                        Honorandissime!<note xml:id="note.1">For his letter see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Hegedűs</hi> 1997, 131.</note></p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Cum per reverendissimum dominum meum cancellarium regium huc
                        <placeName>Viennam</placeName> missus fuissem, reperi officialem
                    Dominationis Vestrae Reverendissimae dominum <persName>Ioannem
                        Czegledinum</persName><note xml:id="note.2">János Czeglédi, Provisor of
                        Oláh. He was Canon of the Cathedral Chapter of Győr between 1534–1541, and
                        Canon of Veszprém from 1543, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Karácsonyi–Kollányi</hi> 1909, 275, 299, and <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Bedy</hi> 1938, 359–360.</note> affinem meum et ne sine istis ad
                    Dominationem Vestram Reverendissimam proficisceretur, volui de quibusdam
                    novitatibus eandem certiorem facere.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">Explorator noster sabbato proxime praeterito<note xml:id="note.3">28
                        August.</note> rediit ad <placeName>Posonium</placeName>,<note
                        xml:id="note.4">Bratislava.</note> qui retulit <persName>caesarum
                        Turcarum</persName> feria secunda ante Bartholomei<note xml:id="note.5">St.
                        Bartholomew’s Day is on 24 August; <hi rend="italic">feria secunda ante
                            Bartholomei</hi> was on 23 August.</note> in possessionem
                        <placeName>Kunlewd</placeName><note xml:id="note.6">Kömlőd.</note> ab
                        <placeName>Buda</placeName> sex milliaribus<note xml:id="note.7">The extent
                        of an old Hungarian mile depended on the geography. It was between 1.74–8.35
                        kilometres, but sometimes it went up to 11.3 kilometres. If we calculate
                        with about 8 kilometres per one old Hungarian mile, we get about 50
                        kilometres, which distance is in accordance with the distance between Buda
                        and Kömlőd, see <hi rend="smallcap">Bogdán</hi> 1987, 58.</note> reliquisse.
                    Procursores autem Turci eodem die in suburbio civitatis Budensis affuerunt.
                    Feria quinta aut sexta post Bartholomei<note xml:id="note.8">On Thursday or
                        Friday after St. Bartolomew’s, i.e. 26 or 27 August.</note><persName>Ioannes
                        Zapoliensis</persName><note xml:id="note.9">János Szapolyai (1487–1540) or
                        King John I was Voivode of Transylvania before his coronation. He had
                        himself proclaimed king at the Diet of Székesfehérvár on 10 November, 1526
                        as a result of which civil war broke out.</note> ingressus est
                        <placeName>Albam Regalem</placeName><note xml:id="note.10"
                        >Székesfehérvár.</note> et iisdem diebus caesar ipse undequaque circumdedit
                    castrum et civitatem Budensem. Refertur, quod iam ceperit
                        <placeName>Budam</placeName>.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">[2.] Cum haec ita agerentur, <persName>Thomas Nadasdi</persName> ad
                    explorandum pro se exiverat de castro utcumque ab Hungaris vel Turcis notus:
                    insecuti sunt eum, ut vix castrum ingressus est. Sabbato tunc sequenti Turcae et
                    Hungari fuerunt <placeName>Strigonii</placeName>,<note xml:id="note.11"
                        >Esztergom.</note> qui statim castrum sagittare coeperunt: dummodo
                        <persName>Strigoniensis</persName><note xml:id="note.12">Pál Várday.</note>
                    est in castro suo <placeName>Dregel</placeName>,<note xml:id="note.13"
                        >Drégely.</note> nulla spes nobis est, ut Budense castrum,
                        <placeName>Wyssegrad</placeName>,<note xml:id="note.14"
                        >Visegrád.</note><placeName>Strigonium</placeName> non capiatur. Hodie
                        <placeName>Viennam</placeName> ruit fama, quales laucigeni<note
                        xml:id="note.15">Or <hi rend="italic">lancigeri</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Landsknechts</hi>, meaning infantrymen of peasant origin.</note>
                    Hungaros ex castro Posoniensi simulcum <persName>Ioanne Zalay</persName><note
                        xml:id="note.16">János Szalay of Kerecsény, <hi rend="italic">ispán</hi> of
                        Pozsony county from 1527. He remained loyal to King Ferdinand I till the
                        end. One of his best friends was Tamás Nádasdy, with whom he corresponded as
                        well, see <hi rend="smallcap">Bessenyei</hi> 1994, passim.</note>
                    expulissent, tamen ut hoc revera scribere possum, incertum adhuc habeo. Hodie
                    civitas Viennensis fecit computum, quantum peditum et equitum haec potest:
                        <persName>caesar</persName> Romanorum est in <placeName>Italia</placeName>,
                    habet pacem perpetuam cum sancto pontifice, cum <persName>rege
                        Francorum</persName>, cum <persName>rege Angliae</persName>, ne forte Deus
                    ex eorum unione defensioni nostrae attendet, quod ut fiat, Deum deprecemur.
                    Turca habet in exercitu suo III <hi rend="smallcap">CM</hi><note
                        xml:id="note.17">Unclear reading. <hi rend="italic">CM</hi> probably means
                        100,000, so III<hi rend="super">CM</hi> would mean 300,000 of
                        infantrymen.</note> et in aqua I<hi rend="super">CM</hi> ingenia magna pro
                        muro<note xml:id="note.18">Battering cannons, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Simon</hi> 2008, 318.</note> VI<hi rend="smallcap">C</hi><note
                        xml:id="note.19">VI<hi rend="super">C</hi> probably means 600.</note>
                    Hungari ab ipsis non impediuntur, ut eo magis ipsos ad se alliciat, sed videant
                    ipsi in </p>
                <pb facs="15290901_1_2.jpg"/>
                <p xml:id="p.5">futurum, ut fertur Turca vult totam <placeName>Austriam</placeName>
                    hac hieme suae <choice>
                        <orig>ditionae</orig>
                        <supplied>ditioni</supplied>
                    </choice> dare. Maxima res est, quod huzarones tam a domino palatino, quam a
                    domino cancellario ad Turcas eunt, illicque libentius esse voluit, quam
                    nobiscum, cum nuper ex
                        <placeName>Buda</placeName><placeName>Posonium</placeName> veniremus,
                    provisor domini mei <persName>Ioannes Redneky</persName><note xml:id="note.20"
                        >János Redneki, the accountant of the income of the Bishop of Veszprém,
                        previous hussar at the court of King Louis II, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Fógel</hi> 1917, 62.</note> cum quarta equitibus ad
                        <persName>Ioannem</persName> ivit, alii itidem faciunt, quid deinde
                    sequetur, Deus novit. Haec volui Dominationi Vestrae Reverendissimae scribere,
                    ne me negligentem putare posset, cui me iterum commendo.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.6"><placeName>Viennae</placeName> feria tertia in festo Beati Egidii
                    abbatis 1529.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.7">
                    <seg type="signature">Servitor Sigismundus Zeremlyeny</seg>
                    <note xml:id="note.21">Zsigmond Szeremlényi was Royal Secretary.</note>
                </p>
                <pb/>
            </div>
            <div style="handwritten" type="verso" xml:id="d.2">
                <head>On the other side:</head>
                <p xml:id="p.8"> Reverendo Domino Nicolao Olah, custodi Albensi, utrariumque
                    maiestatum Secretario, Domino meo Honorandissimo.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
